04558nam a22006615i 9780226532479DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017036849  a9780226532479  a(DE-B1597)524625  a(OCoLC)1028637805  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBF1125b.O33 2018 4aBF1125b.O33 2018 7aREL0000002bisacsh1 aOgden, Emily, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCredulity :bA Cultural History of US Mesmerism /cEmily Ogden. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aClass 200: New Studies in Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tOut on Credulity! An Introduction -- t1. It Does Not Exist: Animal Magnetism Before It Was True -- t2. Beyond Radical Enchantment: Mesmerizing Laborers in the Americas -- t3. In Imagination: Traveling Clairvoyance and the Suspension of Disbelief -- t4. Out of Character: Phrenomesmerism and the Secular Agent -- t5. The Spirit of Benjamin Franklin -- tCoda: Bagging the Idol -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the 1830s to the Civil War, Americans could be found putting each other into trances for fun and profit in parlors, on stage, and in medical consulting rooms. They were performing mesmerism. Surprisingly central to literature and culture of the period, mesmerism embraced a variety of phenomena, including mind control, spirit travel, and clairvoyance. Although it had been debunked by Benjamin Franklin in late eighteenth-century France, the practice nonetheless enjoyed a decades-long resurgence in the United States. Emily Ogden here offers the first comprehensive account of those boom years. Credulity tells the fascinating story of mesmerism’s spread from the plantations of the French Antilles to the textile factory cities of 1830s New England. As it proliferated along the Eastern seaboard, this occult movement attracted attention from Ralph Waldo Emerson’s circle and ignited the nineteenth-century equivalent of flame wars in the major newspapers. But mesmerism was not simply the last gasp of magic in modern times. Far from being magicians themselves, mesmerists claimed to provide the first rational means of manipulating the credulous human tendencies that had underwritten past superstitions. Now, rather than propping up the powers of oracles and false gods, these tendencies served modern ends such as labor supervision, education, and mediated communication. Neither an atavistic throwback nor a radical alternative, mesmerism was part and parcel of the modern. Credulity offers us a new way of understanding the place of enchantment in secularizing America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCredulityzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCredulity-United States-History-19th century. 0aMesmerismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMesmerism-United States-History-19th century. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aagency.  aanimal magnetism.  aantebellum United States.  abelief.  aenchantment.  amesmerism.  amodernity.  aoccult.  asecularization.  aspiritualism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022653216540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226532479423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226532479/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles